s steel through six distinct phases: birth, formation, display, dispersal, construction, and return. By following the life of steel from the collection of raw minerals to the distribution and disposal of finished products, Christensen challenges the traditional narrative that steel was simply the primary material responsible for architectural modernism.Based on the premise that building materials are as much a part of the natural world as they are of a building, this groundbreaking book rewrites an important chapter of architectural history. It will be welcomed by specialists in architectural history, nineteenth-century studies, environmental history, German studies, modernist studies, and the Anthropocene.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecture, Moderny19th century. 0aBuilding, Iron and steelxHistoryy19th century. 0aSteel industry and tradexEnvironmental aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aSteel industry and tradexEnvironmental aspectsxHistoryy19thcentury. 0aSteel industry and tradexHistoryy19th century. 0aSteel industry and tradezGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aGermany.  aKrupp.  aSecond Industrial Revolution.  aThyssen.  aasphalt.  acompany towns.  aecology.  afactories.  ahistory of pollution.  aindustrial exhibitions.  amaterial-centered history.  amateriality.  amining.  aprefabrication.  arecycling.  ascrap trades.  aslag.  asteel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2022z9783110992793oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz9783110993